In the mathematical theory of computation, the '''Solovay–Kitaev theorem''' says, roughly, that if a set of single-[[qubit]] [[quantum gate]]s generates a [[Dense subset|dense]] [[subset]] of [[SU(2)]] then that set is guaranteed to fill SU(2) quickly, which means good approximations to any desired gate can be created using fairly short sequences of gates from the generating set. It is one of the most important fundamental results in the field of [[Quantum computing|quantum computation]].<ref>{{cite arxiv|last=Dawson|first=Christopher M.|last2=Nielsen|first2=Michael A.|date=2005-05-05|title=The Solovay-Kitaev algorithm|eprint=quant-ph/0505030}}</ref> [[Robert M. Solovay]] and [[Alexei Kitaev]] jointly came up with and proved the theorem.

